WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:04.100
Okay. Welcome everybody. This is a session on KRAS inhibitors from discovery to

2
00:00:04.180 --> 00:00:05.240
patient outcomes.

3
00:00:06.080 --> 00:00:07.060
Thanks to all of you for coming.

4
00:00:08.320 --> 00:00:12.080
So I'm Frank McCormick. I'm the chair of the session today, and I'm going to give a

5
00:00:12.100 --> 00:00:15.460
bit of background on RAS biology, so we're all on the same page in understanding

6
00:00:15.480 --> 00:00:19.320
the challenges of targeting RAS and what RAS proteins do in normal cells

7
00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:20.340
and in cancer cells.

8
00:00:21.320 --> 00:00:24.840
I will very briefly summarize attempts to target downstream effectors, particularly

9
00:00:24.900 --> 00:00:28.490
RAF and PI3 kinase alpha, and then summarize again very

10
00:00:28.500 --> 00:00:32.420
briefly some of our efforts to develop KRAS inhibitors at

11
00:00:32.439 --> 00:00:35.860
the Frederick National Lab in collaboration with BridgeBio Oncology

12
00:00:35.920 --> 00:00:36.540
Therapeutics.

13
00:00:37.400 --> 00:00:41.330
And then I will hand over the podium to my friend and colleague, Cameron Pitt, and

14
00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:44.500
then on to Mallika Singh, the finale. Is that good?

15
00:00:45.740 --> 00:00:47.199
Good. Okay, let's go.

16
00:00:48.900 --> 00:00:49.000
So

17
00:00:49.980 --> 00:00:52.140
let's skip through my disclosures so you don't have time to read them.

18
00:00:53.140 --> 00:00:56.820
Okay. So first of all, some background on the RAS pathway

19
00:00:57.140 --> 00:01:00.500
and also a way of introducing people in my lab who are actually working on this

20
00:01:00.540 --> 00:01:00.940
pathway.

21
00:01:01.980 --> 00:01:05.380
So, I think you're all well aware that RTKs activate RAS

22
00:01:05.401 --> 00:01:09.040
through activation of SOS, which puts RAS proteins from the inactive

23
00:01:09.140 --> 00:01:12.700
state into the active state, and then in normal cells,

24
00:01:13.220 --> 00:01:17.030
RAS's only function that we know of in normal cells is to activate the MAP

25
00:01:17.040 --> 00:01:17.880
kinase pathway.

26
00:01:18.900 --> 00:01:22.530
RAS proteins are turned off by GAPs, of which neurofibromin and

27
00:01:22.560 --> 00:01:26.420
RASA2 and A3 seem to be the major GAPs that work on canonical RAS

28
00:01:26.440 --> 00:01:30.200
proteins. So these proteins kick RAS back into the inactive state, and we go back

29
00:01:30.240 --> 00:01:30.840
to where we were.

30
00:01:32.120 --> 00:01:32.280
So,

31
00:01:33.320 --> 00:01:36.480
you may think that this is like textbook stuff and all, everything is known about

32
00:01:36.520 --> 00:01:39.960
the RAS pathway that needs to be known, but you'd be wrong because some of what is

33
00:01:39.980 --> 00:01:42.840
in the textbooks is actually not correct or requires revision.

34
00:01:44.200 --> 00:01:48.060
For example, we think the mechanism by which RAS proteins get activated

35
00:01:48.100 --> 00:01:51.940
by SOS needs revision, and Matt Sale in my lab, a

36
00:01:51.960 --> 00:01:55.660
very brilliant postdoctoral fellow, has been working on a new

37
00:01:55.700 --> 00:01:58.140
mechanism for activation of SOS.

38
00:01:59.540 --> 00:02:03.400
Part of the activation of RAS is thought to involve the

39
00:02:03.440 --> 00:02:05.190
SHP2 protein tyrosine phosphatase.

40
00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:09.509
And Matt has shown that in fact, in contrast to what's been in the literature,

41
00:02:09.961 --> 00:02:13.760
the phosphatase activity of SHP2 is irrelevant to its role in

42
00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:17.260
activating RAS. And we won't have time to talk about this today, but it's part of a

43
00:02:17.320 --> 00:02:19.900
story that's kind of late breaking.

44
00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.900
I have to say that our analysis of the phosphatase activity of SHP2 and

45
00:02:23.920 --> 00:02:27.660
its role in signaling has been done in kind of parallel with Ben Neal, who's made

46
00:02:27.700 --> 00:02:31.620
similar observations. And Ben will be presenting his data at the major

47
00:02:31.680 --> 00:02:35.560
symposium on Monday at 12:30. So again, we coordinated our results even though

48
00:02:35.580 --> 00:02:37.540
we've found the same thing independently.

49
00:02:37.580 --> 00:02:41.340
It's a paradigm shift in how SHP2 works in activating

50
00:02:41.940 --> 00:02:42.660
RAS proteins.

51
00:02:44.340 --> 00:02:48.300
We still don't really understand exactly the role of the SHOC2 PP1C complex that we

52
00:02:48.340 --> 00:02:52.220
discovered back in 2006, and which RAS proteins are involved in this, whether

53
00:02:52.260 --> 00:02:53.220
it's mRAS

54
00:02:54.080 --> 00:02:57.540
or other canonical RAS proteins. And there's a role for

55
00:02:57.580 --> 00:03:01.280
RIT1 in activating RAF indirectly,

56
00:03:01.620 --> 00:03:04.920
and this protein is regulated by LZTR1 by degradation, and

57
00:03:05.020 --> 00:03:08.790
LZTR1 may have a role in degrading other proteins as

58
00:03:08.820 --> 00:03:12.620
well. So still lots of things to work on in this pathway, some of which are

59
00:03:12.660 --> 00:03:16.320
relevant to normal cell signaling and some more in the context of cancer.

60
00:03:17.060 --> 00:03:20.460
And a plug for Miranda, who's in the audience, I think somewhere here. Is she?

61
00:03:21.940 --> 00:03:24.500
Right there. She has a poster on Monday.

62
00:03:24.840 --> 00:03:27.300
And I urge you all to go and look at her poster.

63
00:03:27.840 --> 00:03:31.480
She's been interested in how RRAS2 and other RAS proteins

64
00:03:31.960 --> 00:03:35.900
are involved in activating PI3 kinase, particularly in the context of helico

65
00:03:35.920 --> 00:03:38.359
mutations of PI3 kinase in human cancer.

66
00:03:38.900 --> 00:03:42.760
And then Rony Francois, who may be in the audience somewhere, also has a

67
00:03:42.780 --> 00:03:46.560
poster, which I would urge you to look at. Hi, Rony.

68
00:03:47.900 --> 00:03:48.920
Should have guessed he'd be in the front row.

69
00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:53.740
Rony has been looking at various aspects of SHOC2 and including trying to find out

70
00:03:53.780 --> 00:03:54.970
what the phosphatase is that

71
00:03:55.860 --> 00:03:59.420
actually phosphorylates RAF1 on the negative phosphorylation site.

72
00:04:01.880 --> 00:04:03.940
So that's how things work in normal cells.

73
00:04:03.980 --> 00:04:07.700
And again, in normal cells, there's no evidence that I know of that RAS proteins do

74
00:04:07.760 --> 00:04:09.960
anything except MAP kinase in normal cells.

75
00:04:10.220 --> 00:04:13.600
And if anyone has any evidence, please let me know because we've been trying hard

76
00:04:13.760 --> 00:04:16.940
to find any. However, things are very different in cancer

77
00:04:16.959 --> 00:04:19.921
cells. So they're different in several different ways.

78
00:04:20.940 --> 00:04:24.700
So in cancer cells with mutations in RAS, such as codon 12 and

79
00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:28.520
13 and 61, as you all know, these mutations essentially make RAS

80
00:04:28.530 --> 00:04:31.020
proteins resistant to all forms of GAP.

81
00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:35.060
So RAS proteins accumulate to varying degrees in their

82
00:04:35.120 --> 00:04:38.680
GDP-bound state, and therefore signal downstream more

83
00:04:38.740 --> 00:04:41.420
independently of growth factors in a different way.

84
00:04:42.380 --> 00:04:46.280
So in normal cells, signaling is very controlled and pulsatile, as shown here

85
00:04:46.320 --> 00:04:48.340
by a standard sort of analysis of signaling.

86
00:04:48.420 --> 00:04:51.540
After adding EGF to cells, you get a blip in RAS GTP.

87
00:04:51.620 --> 00:04:54.760
It goes away again. A blip in phospho-ERK goes away again.

88
00:04:55.180 --> 00:04:56.020
And you can measure this

89
00:04:56.940 --> 00:05:00.460
by biochemical means like this or by measuring phospho-ERK in a

90
00:05:00.540 --> 00:05:02.800
single-cell readout, as done by John Auluck here.

91
00:05:03.280 --> 00:05:07.260
And you can see a pulsatile signaling of spikes of MAP kinase

92
00:05:07.520 --> 00:05:09.280
signaling in response to growth factors.

93
00:05:10.080 --> 00:05:13.520
And the key thing here is the more growth factor you add, the more spikes you get.

94
00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:17.640
But every spike is very tightly controlled in terms of its size and its

95
00:05:17.980 --> 00:05:18.500
duration.

96
00:05:19.300 --> 00:05:22.940
And in normal cells, normal cells can interpret different growth factors

97
00:05:22.980 --> 00:05:23.720
differently. So

98
00:05:24.600 --> 00:05:28.450
NGF, EGF, FGF probably create different series of spikes, and

99
00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:32.460
this kind of Morse code is interpreted differently in different contexts and in

100
00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:36.280
different cell types. The outcome of this pathway activation is very

101
00:05:36.320 --> 00:05:38.860
different. It could be proliferation, it could be differentiation, it can be

102
00:05:38.900 --> 00:05:42.700
involved in cognition and many other aspects of cell biology.

103
00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:46.880
But in cancer cells where we have mutant RAS, things are very different.

104
00:05:47.040 --> 00:05:50.820
Now, RAS GTP just stays on the whole time, doesn't really care very much

105
00:05:50.900 --> 00:05:54.280
about adding growth factors. So we go from a very controlled

106
00:05:54.560 --> 00:05:58.460
pulsatile sort of code to signaling into this sort of tonic

107
00:05:58.520 --> 00:06:02.436
noise of phospho-ERK activation.And this conversion from

108
00:06:02.856 --> 00:06:06.556
control to persistent activation of phosphoerk is sufficient to

109
00:06:06.596 --> 00:06:10.116
transform cells. That alone is probably the first step in

110
00:06:10.516 --> 00:06:12.776
transformation driven by MAP kinase.

111
00:06:15.296 --> 00:06:15.476
So

112
00:06:16.436 --> 00:06:20.136
an obvious experiment would be to find drugs that block RAF kinase

113
00:06:20.176 --> 00:06:20.675
activity.

114
00:06:21.536 --> 00:06:23.216
And so we tried this many, many years ago.

115
00:06:23.276 --> 00:06:26.816
Before most of you were born, we developed a RAF inhibitor called sorafenib,

116
00:06:27.336 --> 00:06:31.116
and it worked in many cancer types, pretty much everywhere except in cancers

117
00:06:31.376 --> 00:06:32.156
with mutant RAS.

118
00:06:33.116 --> 00:06:36.656
It's not what we expected. And later on, several

119
00:06:36.736 --> 00:06:39.966
investigators, including one of my heroes, Neil Rosen, who's in the audience right

120
00:06:39.996 --> 00:06:40.456
here,

121
00:06:41.756 --> 00:06:43.256
who I'm quoting here without his permission,

122
00:06:44.216 --> 00:06:47.886
showed that RAF inhibitors create a paradoxical

123
00:06:47.976 --> 00:06:51.636
activation of RAF kinase. So here he's

124
00:06:51.976 --> 00:06:55.776
measured levels of phospho-MEK, a substrate of RAF, and as you increase

125
00:06:55.816 --> 00:06:59.676
doses of different RAF inhibitors, you see an increase in RAF

126
00:06:59.756 --> 00:07:03.276
activity. This is not what we expected at all, just the opposite, in fact,

127
00:07:03.736 --> 00:07:05.415
but it's true of all of these RAF inhibitors.

128
00:07:05.976 --> 00:07:09.066
And we now know, as many of you will know who follow this field, this is because,

129
00:07:09.096 --> 00:07:11.636
again, of paradoxical activation of RAF.

130
00:07:12.376 --> 00:07:16.356
So RAF, we didn't know at the time, but RAF acts as a dimer coupled to RAS in the

131
00:07:16.376 --> 00:07:18.856
plasma membrane, as I'll show you in the next slide.

132
00:07:19.456 --> 00:07:23.176
But if one of these protomers is inhibited by particular drugs like these, the

133
00:07:23.196 --> 00:07:27.126
inactive protomer hyperactivates the wild type or

134
00:07:27.156 --> 00:07:30.536
the drug-free counterpart to give you an increased signal output.

135
00:07:31.416 --> 00:07:35.396
So RAF essentially is booby-trapped so that RAF inhibitors don't work, and that

136
00:07:36.036 --> 00:07:39.956
put a cold shower on the whole field of developing RAF

137
00:07:40.196 --> 00:07:44.016
inhibitors. People have tried to develop paradox breakers, but

138
00:07:44.056 --> 00:07:47.976
this has got even more complicated now because from the work of Mariano

139
00:07:48.036 --> 00:07:48.906
Barbacid and,

140
00:07:50.016 --> 00:07:51.336
more recently, Julian Downward,

141
00:07:52.256 --> 00:07:55.896
it now seems that the RAF proteins, RAF1 particularly, has a scaffold

142
00:07:55.916 --> 00:07:59.636
function. So inhibiting the kinase is not sufficient to turn off RAS

143
00:07:59.676 --> 00:08:03.496
signaling. You actually have to get rid of the protein altogether or prevent the

144
00:08:03.536 --> 00:08:05.356
RAS protein from binding to RAF1.

145
00:08:06.256 --> 00:08:10.056
So there's some structural component of the RAF kinase which is important, at least

146
00:08:10.116 --> 00:08:13.816
from mouse models, which is not addressed by kinase inhibitors.

147
00:08:14.816 --> 00:08:17.016
So we're trying to address that in the lab.

148
00:08:17.336 --> 00:08:20.856
A graduate student just passed her qualifying exams last week.

149
00:08:21.136 --> 00:08:25.096
Maria is working on a project in collaboration with Keyvan Shokat to

150
00:08:25.296 --> 00:08:28.896
find a new way of preventing RAS activating RAF that doesn't cause

151
00:08:28.936 --> 00:08:30.615
paradoxical activation.

152
00:08:31.516 --> 00:08:34.736
But this slide is meant to show you that we were sort of ahead of ourselves in

153
00:08:34.756 --> 00:08:38.476
developing RAF inhibitors early on because the activation process is much more

154
00:08:38.516 --> 00:08:40.557
complicated than we expected.

155
00:08:41.496 --> 00:08:44.956
So we'll start here with the inactive RAF held in the cytoplasm

156
00:08:45.516 --> 00:08:49.136
by a dimer of 14.3.3 proteins, each bound through specific

157
00:08:49.416 --> 00:08:52.576
phosphosites on the RAF protein. So this is the inactive state.

158
00:08:53.076 --> 00:08:56.816
The RAS binding domain, the RBD, is accessible, and when RAS is in the

159
00:08:56.856 --> 00:09:00.456
GTP state, it can bind there and recruit this complex to the plasma

160
00:09:00.496 --> 00:09:04.136
membrane. And in the process of recruiting it, the CRD, the

161
00:09:04.156 --> 00:09:07.626
cysteine-rich domain, which is buried in the RAF protein here, comes

162
00:09:07.676 --> 00:09:11.416
exposed and starts interacting with lipids in the plasma membrane.

163
00:09:11.426 --> 00:09:14.736
So this is the first step towards dimerization and

164
00:09:14.836 --> 00:09:15.436
activation.

165
00:09:16.356 --> 00:09:20.276
Now, the phosphate that kept the 14.3.3 proteins in the inactive state, we

166
00:09:20.316 --> 00:09:23.576
call the molecular handcuffs, that keep the RAF protein inactive.

167
00:09:25.216 --> 00:09:29.096
This phosphorylation site, if it remains phosphorylated, could result

168
00:09:29.156 --> 00:09:33.056
in the reaction going backwards and 14.3.3 binding again to going back to the

169
00:09:33.076 --> 00:09:33.836
inactive state.

170
00:09:34.656 --> 00:09:38.516
So under certain circumstances, a complex that, again, we discovered in

171
00:09:38.876 --> 00:09:42.556
2006, a complex of MRAS, PP1C, and

172
00:09:42.596 --> 00:09:46.136
SHOK2, is recruited to the plasma membrane and dephosphorylates

173
00:09:46.176 --> 00:09:50.116
this phosphate specifically. And that prevents the reaction going backwards and

174
00:09:50.156 --> 00:09:51.976
pushes the whole thing towards activation.

175
00:09:52.816 --> 00:09:56.636
So cancer cells are particularly dependent on SHOK2 much more than normal

176
00:09:56.716 --> 00:10:00.276
cells. Lucy Young in the lab has shown that you don't need to dephosphorylate

177
00:10:00.596 --> 00:10:04.276
T259 to go through dimerization. But

178
00:10:04.936 --> 00:10:08.336
if you do dephosphorylate, the reaction goes much more efficiently.

179
00:10:09.136 --> 00:10:12.816
So cancer cells depend on this extra step, presumably because the flux through the

180
00:10:12.836 --> 00:10:15.796
pathway is much faster and you can't afford to go backwards.

181
00:10:15.836 --> 00:10:18.816
You just want to keep driving activation of the pathway.

182
00:10:18.836 --> 00:10:21.266
And again, Roni is trying to figure out what the kinase is that puts this

183
00:10:21.276 --> 00:10:23.736
phosphorylation on RAF in the first place.

184
00:10:24.916 --> 00:10:28.056
So still a lot to learn about this activation process.

185
00:10:29.056 --> 00:10:32.966
Debbie Morrison and Michael Eck and the group at Frederick have solved

186
00:10:32.996 --> 00:10:35.336
various components of this pathway

187
00:10:36.176 --> 00:10:37.856
by crystallography or by cryo-EM.

188
00:10:38.436 --> 00:10:42.236
We haven't yet got a full idea of what the whole activation complex looks

189
00:10:42.276 --> 00:10:46.196
like. And we're really keen to know this because we know that activation of RAF in

190
00:10:46.256 --> 00:10:48.546
cancer cells is different to normal cells, because

191
00:10:49.496 --> 00:10:53.156
RAS cancer cells depend on RAF1 exclusively to

192
00:10:53.236 --> 00:10:56.916
activate the MAP kinase pathway in cancer, whereas normal cells don't care

193
00:10:56.956 --> 00:10:59.216
about which isoform of RAF is engaged.

194
00:10:59.576 --> 00:11:03.216
So there are real differences between the signaling in normal cells and

195
00:11:03.236 --> 00:11:06.316
in cancer cells we might be able to exploit if we understood more about the

196
00:11:06.356 --> 00:11:08.736
biochemistry. So that's what we're trying to do.

197
00:11:11.076 --> 00:11:13.576
Now, you all know from textbooks, if you look up,

198
00:11:14.456 --> 00:11:18.026
for example, on Google what the RAS proteins do, you get a number of figures like

199
00:11:18.076 --> 00:11:21.656
this from different textbooks showing that RAS can activate a whole range of

200
00:11:21.696 --> 00:11:23.096
different downstream effectors.

201
00:11:23.976 --> 00:11:26.856
If you ask ChatGPT or Claude, as we now use,

202
00:11:27.696 --> 00:11:30.516
you get the answer that the major effector is MAP kinase.

203
00:11:30.876 --> 00:11:34.256
A secondary one, which is important in most cancers, is PI3 kinase.

204
00:11:34.606 --> 00:11:37.456
And then occasionally, RalGDS is a real effector.

205
00:11:38.296 --> 00:11:41.616
And we think the truth is much along these lines, that some of these engagements

206
00:11:41.676 --> 00:11:45.396
are important in very specific cell types under certain circumstances,

207
00:11:45.496 --> 00:11:49.156
but mostly MAP kinase is critical, and in some tumor cells,

208
00:11:49.876 --> 00:11:52.906
some alleles of RAS activate PI3 kinase, and that helps

209
00:11:53.856 --> 00:11:55.836
the transformed phenotype dramatically.

210
00:11:56.896 --> 00:12:00.876
And other downstream effectors are most likely, again, important in certain

211
00:12:00.916 --> 00:12:03.344
contexts.So,

212
00:12:04.224 --> 00:12:05.564
how can this possibly be that a

213
00:12:06.384 --> 00:12:10.324
protein like Ras can interact with so many different effectors, each of which has a

214
00:12:10.364 --> 00:12:11.543
completely different structure?

215
00:12:12.444 --> 00:12:15.204
So these aren't all conserved family members, they're all completely different

216
00:12:15.244 --> 00:12:15.684
proteins.

217
00:12:16.484 --> 00:12:17.124
And at least

218
00:12:17.944 --> 00:12:19.064
one answer is this, that

219
00:12:20.504 --> 00:12:23.844
Ras proteins, the canonical Ras proteins, are part of a super family of related

220
00:12:23.884 --> 00:12:27.794
proteins, Ras, Ras2, Raf-1, M-Ras, and

221
00:12:27.844 --> 00:12:31.804
others. Each of these is regulated by GAPs and GEFs, some of them shared,

222
00:12:31.884 --> 00:12:35.183
some of them unique, and they activate their own private pathways.

223
00:12:35.744 --> 00:12:39.684
And in normal cells, these swim lanes are kept separate because of the affinity

224
00:12:39.784 --> 00:12:43.584
of Ras proteins for their effectors basically prevents them crossing over

225
00:12:43.944 --> 00:12:44.964
into the other swim lanes.

226
00:12:46.044 --> 00:12:49.584
So they are very well controlled, spatially and temporarily.

227
00:12:50.724 --> 00:12:54.464
But if you mutate Ras and it starts to accumulate in the active state and

228
00:12:54.504 --> 00:12:57.684
frequently in tumor cells, you overexpress Ras to higher levels,

229
00:12:58.384 --> 00:13:02.324
then the mutant Ras protein can cross over into the other swim lanes

230
00:13:02.384 --> 00:13:06.324
and now pick up effectors that are normally meant to be engaged by

231
00:13:06.384 --> 00:13:08.104
these closely related family members.

232
00:13:09.044 --> 00:13:12.604
And this kind of promiscuity that's a neo function of Ras in tumor cells

233
00:13:12.844 --> 00:13:16.164
presents therapeutic opportunities, obviously, because these interactions we don't

234
00:13:16.174 --> 00:13:17.584
think happen normally.

235
00:13:18.904 --> 00:13:22.864
Somanchu, Frederick, and myself have just written a review on this topic

236
00:13:23.184 --> 00:13:27.164
to explain from a structural level how these Ras family proteins can

237
00:13:27.204 --> 00:13:29.784
actually cross over and interact with one another.

238
00:13:30.624 --> 00:13:34.264
So these are structures of Ras proteins bound to either Raf or PI3 kinase and

239
00:13:34.324 --> 00:13:36.724
RalGDS, and these are the points of contact.

240
00:13:37.184 --> 00:13:40.924
And on these alignments here, you can see from these blocks where the things are

241
00:13:40.964 --> 00:13:44.944
identical, most of the Ras proteins share a very similar identical core,

242
00:13:45.444 --> 00:13:47.204
but as you can see from this red and

243
00:13:48.004 --> 00:13:48.464
green here,

244
00:13:50.364 --> 00:13:54.024
Ras subtypes differ in specific amino acids to give maybe 10 to

245
00:13:54.144 --> 00:13:56.844
20-fold difference in binding between different effectors.

246
00:13:57.224 --> 00:14:00.944
That seemed to be enough to keep them compartmentalized in normal cells, but again,

247
00:14:00.964 --> 00:14:04.304
when you overexpress them, it's enough to allow them to cross over.

248
00:14:05.104 --> 00:14:07.464
So this will be published soon and you can dig in deeper.

249
00:14:09.404 --> 00:14:12.664
So we've taken advantage of one of these interactions, that is the interaction

250
00:14:12.684 --> 00:14:16.484
between K-Ras and P110 alpha, to develop a drug we call the breaker,

251
00:14:16.844 --> 00:14:20.444
which is now in clinical trials. This is a drug that binds to PI3

252
00:14:20.484 --> 00:14:24.154
kinase alpha at the Ras binding domain, this is up here, and

253
00:14:24.164 --> 00:14:25.604
prevents any Ras protein

254
00:14:26.584 --> 00:14:29.524
binding at this site, with one or two exceptions.

255
00:14:30.424 --> 00:14:34.404
So normally, K-Ras binds to PI3 kinase alpha at about 20 micromolar

256
00:14:35.484 --> 00:14:38.064
KD, which is not enough to have any effect in cells.

257
00:14:38.104 --> 00:14:41.904
In fact, this interaction is kind of hard to detect by standard pull down

258
00:14:41.944 --> 00:14:43.244
methods, although it can be done.

259
00:14:44.124 --> 00:14:47.544
But in the presence of a glue compound that we discovered in collaboration with

260
00:14:47.584 --> 00:14:51.384
Daiichi Sankyo, we're able to stick K-Ras onto PI3 kinase

261
00:14:51.464 --> 00:14:55.284
alpha, increase the affinity down to six nanomolar, and then solve

