281
00:15:59.484 --> 00:15:59.874
And that is

282
00:16:01.984 --> 00:16:05.724
mutant Ras proteins, as well as activating effectors directly, are

283
00:16:05.764 --> 00:16:07.304
involved in cell-cell contact.

284
00:16:08.164 --> 00:16:12.064
Transformation was originally defined as a process in which transformed cells

285
00:16:12.344 --> 00:16:15.564
overcome cell-cell contact inhibition. That's a hallmark of cancer.

286
00:16:16.284 --> 00:16:19.124
So I'm just showing you this to remind you that Ras proteins have other biology

287
00:16:19.164 --> 00:16:21.744
other than just activation of effector pathways.

288
00:16:22.444 --> 00:16:26.424
So this little example here, this is the ephrin signaling family, which is the

289
00:16:26.444 --> 00:16:29.944
most abundant form of tyrosine kinases in the genome.

290
00:16:29.964 --> 00:16:33.874
It's 13 different members. And the cool thing about this is that in one

291
00:16:33.964 --> 00:16:37.804
cell presents the ligand, ephrin ligand, and the other cell

292
00:16:37.864 --> 00:16:41.084
is the recipient of this signal, presents the receptor.

293
00:16:41.764 --> 00:16:45.704
And when the ligand binds to the receptor, it sends a signal to the receiving cell,

294
00:16:45.784 --> 00:16:49.524
obviously. And this is often a negative signal, which stops cells from growing.

295
00:16:50.384 --> 00:16:52.184
So this is how cells find their way around the body.

296
00:16:52.804 --> 00:16:55.044
So such as, for example, during neurite outgrowth.

297
00:16:56.304 --> 00:16:58.824
One cell comes to a point where there's ephrins, and the

298
00:16:59.664 --> 00:17:02.504
receiving cell says, "Go away," and it goes somewhere else.

299
00:17:02.984 --> 00:17:05.114
So this is how cells know where they're supposed to be and where they're not

300
00:17:05.124 --> 00:17:05.704
supposed to be.

301
00:17:07.224 --> 00:17:10.664
Now, ephrin B itself, the ephrin receptor, is a tumor suppressor, and it

302
00:17:10.704 --> 00:17:14.585
allows malignant progression of colon cancer, shown from Hans Clevers.

303
00:17:15.214 --> 00:17:19.024
And we now think this is because mutant Ras in colon cancer enables these cells to

304
00:17:19.065 --> 00:17:22.684
escape from negative signals through this ephrin signaling system.

305
00:17:23.565 --> 00:17:27.394
So this experiment was done by Antonio Navarro when he was a graduate student in

306
00:17:27.404 --> 00:17:29.864
the lab in collaboration with our postdoc, Pao, at the time.

307
00:17:30.544 --> 00:17:34.324
This shows you that if you add soluble ephrin ligand to cells, as shown

308
00:17:34.384 --> 00:17:37.103
here, you actually inhibit the MAP kinase pathway.

309
00:17:37.384 --> 00:17:41.204
So you see a dose-dependent inhibition of phospho work in response to the

310
00:17:41.244 --> 00:17:45.124
ligand. So this is a receptor tyrosine kinase, but it's a negative one.

311
00:17:45.544 --> 00:17:48.944
And it's negative because it recruits Ras A1 GAP to the

312
00:17:49.144 --> 00:17:51.004
membrane, where it turns off Ras.

313
00:17:51.904 --> 00:17:55.844
If you get rid of Ras A1 GAP by knocking it out, then ephrin signaling goes the

314
00:17:55.884 --> 00:17:58.624
other way and is now a positive signal in the cell.

315
00:17:59.884 --> 00:18:02.064
So mutant Ras, of course, is resistant to GAPs.

316
00:18:02.444 --> 00:18:06.204
So mutant Ras proteins can't tell when they're being told to go away by

317
00:18:06.244 --> 00:18:10.152
ephrins in the neighboring cells.So the presence of a mutant protein then makes the

318
00:18:10.192 --> 00:18:14.072
cell able to travel around the body and migrate and metastasize,

319
00:18:14.972 --> 00:18:18.642
and completely ignore negative signals from ephrins, would normally stop it from

320
00:18:18.692 --> 00:18:19.212
proliferating.

321
00:18:21.152 --> 00:18:22.842
I guess pretty cool, right? Thank you.

322
00:18:25.312 --> 00:18:25.472
Okay,

323
00:18:26.312 --> 00:18:27.392
enough Ras biology.

